\begin_layout Paragraph
Buyer and seller preference heterogeneity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two dimensions of heterogeneity in the matching market.
 First, each seller has heterogeneous match payoff across buyers.
 Second, different seller have different payoff functions over jobs.
 Concerning the platform's information disclosure problem, I need the following
 pieces of notation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be buyer type, with the interpretation that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the buyer characteristics 
\bar under
observed
\bar default
 by the platform.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Buyer type 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 captures the payoff-relevant information the platform elicits from the
 buyer about the job, passively from the buyer's cookies and queries or
 actively by asking questions.
 For example, on Uber, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 would include rider's destination; on Airbnb, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 would include guest's race, age and gender.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The space of buyer types 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a compact subset of Euclidean space.
 Distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with full support.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 be seller type, with the interpretation that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the seller characteristics 
\bar under
unobserved
\bar default
 by the platform.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Seller type 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 captures the payoff-relevant information the platform did not elicit from
 sellers by whatever reason – costly, unethical, etc.
 For example, on Uber, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 would include the driver's preference for long rides and traffic; on Airbnb,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 would include the host's preference for his guest's age, gender, socio-economic
 status, race, etc.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The space of seller types 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a compact subset of Euclidean space.
 Distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with full support that admits density 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is differentiable on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Seller profit for one match is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x,y)$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is continuous and for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x,y)>0$
\end_inset

.
 Buyer net match payoff is 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y)$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that all incoming buyers have non-negative match payoff:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(x,y)\geq0.\label{eq:buyer-net-payoff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Platform: Information intermediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The platform plays a signaling game with sellers.
 The platform observes buyer type 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and chooses how to reveal it to sellers.
 Sellers do not receive any additional information about 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 outside of what the platform tells them.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\Delta(X)$
\end_inset

 be the set of all posterior distributions over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Information disclosure policy
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Delta(S)$
\end_inset

 is a probability distribution of posteriors.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a compact subset of a Euclidean space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(S)$
\end_inset

 is the set of Borel-measurable probability distributions with the weak-*
 topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The interpretation is 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 is the platform's signal to the seller, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(S')$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of buyers with signals 
\begin_inset Formula $S'\subset S$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I focus on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

public
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 signaling when the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 applies to all seller.
 I am not studying the mechanism design problem where the platform tries
 to elicit or learn the seller’s type 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and tailor the disclosure policy to seller type.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KLMZ-wp"

\end_inset

 find in the one-shot signaling game with linear payoffs that public signaling
 is equivalent to private signaling.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that a disclosure policy can be seen as a two-stage lottery on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 whose reduced lottery is prior 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The two-stage lottery framework for disclosure is adopted from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BBM15"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of possible disclosure policies is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \lambda\in\Delta(S)\colon\int s\lambda(ds)\sim F\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

 Full disclosure policy, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{FD}$
\end_inset

, perfectly reveals buyer type 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to the sellers.
 No disclosure policy fully conceals 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Disclosure policy 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda'$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
coarser
\emph default
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda''$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda'$
\end_inset

 is a Blackwell garbling of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda''$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the platform can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda'$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda''$
\end_inset

 by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda''$
\end_inset

 and partially concealing some 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

's.
 When a buyer of type 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 arrives, the platform draws a signal according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and shows it to the seller.
 The seller knows the platform's choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, and so his interpretation of a signal as a posterior is correct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Steady state distribution of sellers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A steady state of the matching process is characterized by the fraction
 of available sellers of every type and their acceptance rates.
 Formally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 be the acceptance rate of type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 available sellers, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(y)$
\end_inset

 be the type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset


\emph on
 utilization rate
\emph default
 – the fraction of type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers who are busy.
 Denote the total fraction of busy sellers by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}:=\int_{Y}\rho(y)dG(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a steady state, the flow of sellers who become busy is equal to the flow
 of workers who become available.
 The available-to-busy flow is equal to the buyer flow type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers receive times their acceptance rate.
 Since buyer get distributed uniformly across the available sellers, the
 buyer flow to type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\frac{(1-\rho(y))g(y)}{1-\bar{\rho}}$
\end_inset

.
 The acceptance rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the available-to-busy flow is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\frac{(1-\rho(y))g(y)}{1-\bar{\rho}}\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

.
 The busy-to-available flow is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\rho(y)/\tau$
\end_inset

 because the mass of busy 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-sellers is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\rho(y)$
\end_inset

, and jobs are completed in time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, in a steady state, we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta\frac{(1-\rho(y))g(y)}{1-\bar{\rho}}\alpha(y)=\frac{g(y)\rho(y)}{\tau},\quad\forall y\in Y.\label{eq:SS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Matching-process-in"

\end_inset

 for the illustration.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../pictures/match_dynamics_pics/match_steady_state_complete.eps
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Matching process in a steady state.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)$
\end_inset

 is the mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-sellers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(y)$
\end_inset

 is utilization rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is the average utilization rate.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Matching-process-in"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Seller dynamic screening problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Buyers arrive at flow rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and get distributed uniformly at random across all available sellers.
 Therefore, each individual available seller experiences a Poisson arrival
 process of buyers, where the rate of the arrival is equal to the buyer-to-selle
r ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta_{A}:=\frac{\beta}{1-\bar{\rho}}\label{eq:beta_A-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mye00"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cite the relevant theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 There is thus a contrast between individual arrival process and aggregate
 arrival process in that the individual arrival process is stochastic while
 the aggregate arrival process is deterministic (a consequence of law of
 large numbers).
 More concretely, an individual seller faces a stochastic arrival process,
 such that over an infinitesimal time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 the probability that one buyer arrives is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}dt+o(dt)$
\end_inset

.
 Jointly, available sellers face the deterministic buyer arrival process,
 such that over time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 the continuum mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}dt$
\end_inset

 of buyers arrive.
 As we show in the rest of this section, stochasticity of individual arrival
 process combined with independent decision-making creates seller coordination
 problem which results in matching inefficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each seller takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}$
\end_inset

 as given
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This follows from the fact that there is a continuum of sellers on the platform,
 and so any individual seller's actions does not affect 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and solves the dynamic optimization problem where for each incoming job
 he observes the platform's signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and based on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, chooses to accept or reject the job in order to maximize his average profit
 flow.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Sellers-repeated-search"

\end_inset

 for the illustration of the seller dynamic optimization problem.
 The expected profit for seller 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 of a job with signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s,y)=\int_{X}\pi(x,y)s(dx)$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $V(y)$
\end_inset

 the average profit flow when seller of type 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 acts optimally (value function)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, if a seller earns $1 on each job, and time interval between
 starting consequent jobs is 2, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V(y)=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sellers are risk neutral.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and so for the decision-making, it is sufficient to know only the distribution
 of posterior means.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $v(s,y)$
\end_inset

 the value of one new job with signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 includes the option value of rejecting the job and the opportunity cost
 of being unavailable.
 Value of a new job is zero if the seller rejects it, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s,y)-\tau V(y)$
\end_inset

 if he accepts it, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau V(y)$
\end_inset

 is the opportunity cost of accepting due to being unavailable for time
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 There is no discounting.
 Seller optimization problem is then the system of the following two equations:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I consider time average payoff rather than discounted sum because discount
 rate is not essential for my argument.
 However, the results immediately generalize to the case when the seller
 has discount rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{r}=\frac{1-e^{-r\tau}}{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I still use this formulation because in the alternative I have to differentiate
 
\begin_inset Formula $F(c)$
\end_inset

 which is not differentiable in the general case.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
V(y) & = & \beta_{A}\int v(s,y)\lambda(ds)\label{eq:V-via-pi}\\
v(s,y) & = & \max\{0,\pi(s,y)-\tau V(y)\}\label{eq:pi(c)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Seller strategy is function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\cdot,y)\colon S\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 that for every seller type maps a signal to the probability of accepting
 it.
 The seller acceptance rate is the ex ante probability of accepting a job:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha(y)=\int\sigma(s,y)\lambda(ds).\label{eq:alpha}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium definition and existence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am interested in a steady state equilibrium of the market in which the
 sellers take buyer arrival rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}$
\end_inset

 as given and optimize independently, and the seller busy-available flows
 balance out.
 Recall that the exogenous objects in my model are: buyer flow rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, profit function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x,y)$
\end_inset

, distribution of types 
\begin_inset Formula $G(y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

, and completion time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Based on the exogenous objects, a tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma,\bar{\rho})$
\end_inset

 constitute a 
\emph on
steady-state equilibrium
\emph default
 if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
[Optimality] For every type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 seller for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\cdot,y)$
\end_inset

 is an optimal strategy given buyer Poisson arrival rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}=\beta/(1-\bar{\rho})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
[Steady state] Average utilization rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 arises in a steady state when sellers play 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, as shown in {
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:SS"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:alpha"

\end_inset

}.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:Equilibrium-exists-and"

\end_inset

Steady-state equilibrium exists.
 It is unique up to the acceptance of marginal jobs in the follwing sense.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma^{i},\brho^{i})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 are two steady-state equilibria, then (1) 
\begin_inset Formula $\brho^{1}=\brho^{2}$
\end_inset

, and (2) for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{1}(\cdot,y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}(\cdot,y)$
\end_inset

 coincide except on 
\begin_inset Formula $\{s\colon\pi(s,y)=\tau V(y)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the proof in the Appendix, first, I show that for an arbitrary vector
 of acceptance rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

, there is a unique steady state value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\brho$
\end_inset

.
 Then, average utilization 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is increasing and continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 The uniqueness of equilibrium obtains by monotonicity of reaction curves
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:alpha"

\end_inset

, as buyer traffic intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}$
\end_inset

 increases, sellers become more picky and acceptance rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

 decreases.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

 increases, buyers get directed to a smaller set of sellers, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}$
\end_inset

 increases.
 For details see the proof in the Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "proof:eqm-exists"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

