\begin_layout Standard
In this section I discuss how the model maps to the reality in the case
 of Uber, Airbnb and labor platform such as TaskRabbit.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 denotes seller type, i.e.
 the seller's unobserved heterogeneity; 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 denotes buyer type, i.e.
 the information about buyer available to the platform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is an equivalent phrasing of the model which for some real world applicati
ons might be more relevant than the original phrasing.
 In the original phrasing, a buyer first reveals his information 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to the platform, then the platform coarsely matches 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\lambda(x)$
\end_inset

, and finally 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is communicated to sellers.
 Alternatively, I can phrase the model in a different way.
 Type 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 captures all cost-relevant information the buyer possesses.
 The platform's disclosure policy is then a mechanism that partially elicits
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from a buyer.
 That is, the platform gets to observe only 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\lambda(x)$
\end_inset

, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is communicated to sellers.
 For example, the platform asks three questions about a buyer need, which
 imperfectly describes what the buyer wants.
 In this reinterpretation, the platform's information coarsening corresponds
 to coarse elicitation of buyer information.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What is the platform's choice for the examples below? 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Uber.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Drivers receive requests from passenger when they are idle.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is driver's location, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is passenger's destination and star rating.
 Price per mile and minute is fixed (abstract away from surge pricing).
 Drivers do not like short rides or rides to the neighborhoods far removed
 from busy areas.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:indep-vs-coord"

\end_inset

 shows that if drivers have full discretion over accepting or rejecting,
 the driver utilization rates are inefficiently low, and the demand-supply
 fit is suboptimal.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Greg: It's a bit weird to talk about Proposition 2 before introducing it.
 Could you instead talk about what the information disclosure policies of
 the various platforms are - later you can explain why they are what they
 are....
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Airbnb.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hosts are capacity constrained in rooms.
 Once a room is booked for a specific date, the host cannot accept a better
 guest.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 - room quality, location.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 - guest quality, e.g.
 college student vs.
 elderly couple.
 Every host sets his own price that applies to all guests but he may prefer
 to reject certain guests who he expects can be a pain in the neck.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:indep-vs-coord"

\end_inset

 shows that if hosts have full discretion over accepting or rejecting guest
 requests, the apartment utilization rates are inefficiently low, and the
 marketplace is removed from its full potential.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
TaskRabbit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The service providers are capacity constrained because they can do only
 that many tasks per week.
 Once a service provider agreed to do some job, he is constrained in picking
 new tasks.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 - seller skill, specialization.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 - job category, job difficulty, professional/annoying client.
 Service provider sets hourly rate  which applies to all tasks in the category.
 The seller may prefer to reject the tasks which he does not find to be
 a good fit, or too far, or bad timing of the lead.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:indep-vs-coord"

\end_inset

 shows that if service providers have full discretion over accepting or
 rejecting client leads, the utilization of participating labor is inefficiently
 low, and the matching efficiency is suboptimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discussion of the Modeling Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection I discuss in detail the important assumptions of my model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu:single-search-attempt"

\end_inset

Buyers make a single search attempt.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rejection-intolerant buyers is a simplifying assumption that help to avoid
 endogenous distribution of buyer types.
 It captures the real aspect of matching markets that rejections are costly
 to buyers, e.g.
 wasted time, wasted search effort, bidding costs, etc.
 Moreover, buyers often do take rejections badly.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fra15"

\end_inset

 reports that on Airbnb, an initial rejection decreases the probability
 that the guest eventually books any listing by 50%.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
Buyers contact available sellers only.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the paper is to explore the matching frictions that pertain
 to preference heterogeneity and screening.
 Therefore, I assume away the coordination frictions owing to several buyers
 requesting the same seller and the coordination frictions owing to buyer
 requesting unavailable sellers.
 All three types of matching frictions are present in the matching marketplaces
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fra15"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The coordination frictions in matching markets have been extensively studied
 in the theoretical literature (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BSW01,Kir09,Halaburda2013,AJK14"

\end_inset

), and I assume away this channel of matching inefficiency to focus on screening.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu:uniform-assignment"

\end_inset

Buyers contact an available seller chosen uniformly at random
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This assumption has two implications.
 First, seller of any type faces the same intensity of buyer traffic.
 Second, each seller faces the same distribution of buyer jobs.
 This is a simplifying assumption that helps me to focus sellers excessive
 screening problem.
 In the extension 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:General-demand:-workers"

\end_inset

 I show how to deal with a more general demand system where demand for each
 seller type can be different.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Also, Buyer surplus is independent of distribution of available sellers.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
No Excess Demand
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu:no-excess-demand"

\end_inset

Collectively, it is physically possible for sellers to complete every buyer
 job: 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\tau<1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption makes the exposition easier and relaxing it requires more
 notation to deal with either automatic rejections or queues.
 I do this in  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Extensions"

\end_inset

 and show that qualitatively results do not change.
\end_layout

